# Exports go at the bottom of the file

Write functions, types, constants, hooks, components etc. **without** the
`export` keyword in the body of the file, then list every public symbol at
the bottom of the file under a clearly marked "Exports" section. This
keeps the top of the file focused on imports + implementation, and makes
the public surface of the module obvious at a glance.

Applies to all hand-written `.ts` / `.tsx` files under `src/**`.

Do **not** restructure auto-generated files (`routeTree.gen.ts`,
`schema.ts`, etc.) or shadcn/ui primitives that ship with inline exports.

## ❌ Bad

```tsx
export type WorkspaceTab = 'dashboard' | 'companies' | 'users'

export function WorkspaceShell({ org, tab, children }: Props) {
  // ...
}

function TabLink() { /* ... */ }
```

## ✅ Good

```tsx
type WorkspaceTab = 'dashboard' | 'companies' | 'users'

function WorkspaceShell({ org, tab, children }: Props) {
  // ...
}

function TabLink() { /* ... */ }

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------
// Exports
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------

export { WorkspaceShell }
export type { WorkspaceTab }
```

## Notes

- Use `export { Foo }` for values and `export type { Bar }` for types so
  `isolatedModules` / `verbatimModuleSyntax` stay happy.
- Re-exports from other files (`export { x } from './x'`) are fine at
  the top of barrel / index files — they are the file's purpose.
- Default exports follow the same rule: declare `const Page = ...`
  first, then `export default Page` at the bottom.
